validators of mainnet sn12 do their best to not try to hit the same miners at the same time. Each 2 hour period is divided into twelve 5-minute slots and the slots for the miners are divided between validators so that all validators have some miners to run jobs on at all times, but also so that one miner is only being used by one validator at a time.

the miner should "see" a validator on the list of validators periodically taken from the metagraph, if the validator is registered, has validator permit, has sufficient stake etc, however it might not see tasks from that validator for a couple of hours because the validator that just booted doesn't know what happened in the past. Specifically the situation that it is "worried" about is when it has been launched immediately after its relative stake has changed in such a way that it has now become the top24th validator (sn12 for now supports only 24 validators, this will be resolved in the rewrite that we are now working on) BUT there was another validator on that 24th slot up until a minute ago and we really don't want to collide on that slot between us and the old guy, therefore we wait until the 2h slot ends before starting to run jobs (as we know the other guy will then try to calculate his slots and realize he's no longer in top24 and will effectively shut down) (and the miners will ignore it too if it decided to give them jobs anyway)

in the rewrite there will be no 5min slots and no 2h test periods. Validators will test miners aggressively (when they notice a new one or when they boot up), so it should all be more intuitive to operate, however... validators will still not try to overload the blockchain by setting weights too frequently. The weight setting frequency will be low, because if all subnets try to set weights too often, the blockchain will clog up (I mean clog up more than it's clogged already, which is a big problem as it is) and it'll all go up in flames when nobody will be able to do transfers, staking, registration, weight setting

we are introducing a separate feedback mechanism between validators and miners in the rewrite, which will issue (cryptographically signed) score upon completion of every task so that miners will be able to check exactly how they are doing without waiting for weights to be set. I hope this will allow us to make it so that we can set weights even more infrequently, like once per day, making it so that sn12 uses ~1% as many blockchain resources than most of the other subnets

Main advantages over 27:
1. Prevents miner-validator cheaters (where in sn27 a validator can reserve his own miner and shut it down, removing the cost of running the expensive miner hardware but keeping the miner emissions)

8. Hardware classes, eventually with a marketplace which incentivizes providing the hardware that is in demand

there is currently a queue system implemented in the miner which makes sure that the tasks are executed sequentially. This will now be altered so that the miner will be able to execute multiple requests at a time, potentially hundreds.

2. We'll make changes which will increase profitability of the miners even when emissions are low. Emissions, you see, are going to be spread out over 64 subnets, not over 32 like before, so unless TAOUSD is going to go up, we'll have to figure out a way to be profitable for miners. Some of the coding miners have already figured out how to optimize this aspect. The long term vision is to make it so that the validators run a test on all the compute units under their supervision once a day, as opposed to the current 12 times per day, reducing the amount of used compute power (and cost taken by the miner) to a tiny fraction of what it is today. This means that miners will be able to afford better, higher quality hardware without wasting it constantly on useless PoW.
This stands, however, in contract with usability, where normies would like some of their resources to be immediately available.

3. We'll make it so that there are hardware classes with different properties and one of the hardware classes will be a machine that is immediately available (you'll get 3s to provision it, not 4 minutes like currently). We'll also have different variations where miners will be able to properly utilize variety of hardware they horde provides. There will be a class for cost-effective inference of low-vram models, for example (yes, we've finally found a way to put the cheap 4090s to work).

With the first release there will be two hardware classes and I don't know yet what the first is going to be but I can tell you about the second one. It's going to be identical to the first one. This will allow the miners to adjust to the new regime in which they will have to manage their resources between the hardware classes in an optimal way.,

4. With the increasing amount of subnets and validators in race to the bottom of how little "tax" they collect from their delegators, it's going to be harder for them to validate the subnets. I'll try again to set it up with other subnets in such a way that validators can safely and effectively offload most of their compute costs to the Horde, using the resources they are entiteled to use as Tao holders (access to resources provided by the subnets, proportional to stake, is the benefit for bittensor holders - now validators will be able to lower their take below their normal profitability because they can benefit from these resources more than they do from the "staking tax")

5. The community contributions will be continued, but will be minimal for the foreseable future. We've done a lot already: miners, validators and subnet owners use and will use the tools that we've contributed and I'll make a list of those so that we are all aware, but the speed will be reduced. Community members (I'm looking at you, subnet miners) who think tools are important, can reach out to me and I can hand off small assignments which will benefit the mission.

6. We have a bug with the way miner-validator temporary time slot assigner works, which has this property that allows us to deploy a new version of a validator relatively safely without turning off registration. This bug has some consequences in terms of resource availability / usability which I'm slightly uncomforable with, but I can't fix it when the registration needs to be open 24/7.

especially if you compare the development speed of horde to other subnets which haven't changed much since January
